   "source": [
    "# Dynamic circuits - II\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f6411efb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f2c645ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![updates](images/dynamic2/updates.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7bbea44b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Dynamic circuits\n",
    "\n",
    "So far we have used only basic dynamic circuits with measurement and reset pairs.  While useful, these capabilities alone do not enable the full richness of dynamic circuits.  Rather we really want generic expressions involving things like `for/if-else/when` statements that allow for branching.\n",
    "\n",
    "The `qiskit-ibm-provider` allows for passing dynamic circuits with branching logic such as that listed above using `dynamic=True` keyword argument in `backend.run()`.  That is to say, to execute a dynamic circuit job we will use code that looks like:\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "\n",
    "job = backend.run(circuits, shots=shots, dynamic=True)\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "where `dynamic=True` tells the control software to use the updated pathway for dynamic circuits.  Conversely, the default `dynamic=False` option uses the legacy pipeline, and thus cannot handle general dynamic circuits.\n",
    "\n",
    "In what follows we will begin to explore dynamic circuits through several example circuits, starting once again with our BV example"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3ce4950e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n",
    "    At some point in the future, all jobs to IBM Quantum will go through the pathway for dynamic circuits / QASM3.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8285b8a6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Frontmatter"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "29218608",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-30T02:46:10.347665Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-30T02:46:10.331052Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

    "from qiskit import *\n",

    "\n",
    "# Transpiler passes for optimizing dynamic circuits\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.passes.optimization import ResetAfterMeasureSimplification\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load the QASM3 exporter\n",
    "from qiskit import qasm3\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plotting tools\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "try:\n",
    "    plt.style.use('quantum-light')\n",
    "except:\n",
    "    pass\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'"
   ]
  },

    }
   },
   "outputs": [],

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7c133168",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Dynamic BV\n",
    "\n",
    "In our previous look at dynamic BV we had circuits with many measurement+reset pairs.  Repeating our circuit generation code here:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 116,
   "id": "0356eddd",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-29T16:51:25.472930Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-29T16:51:25.459462Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def dynamic_bv(bitstring):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Create a Bernstein-Vazirani circuit from a given bitstring.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "        bitstring (str): A bitstring.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        QuantumCircuit: Output circuit.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(2, len(bitstring))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit\n",
    "    qc.x(1)\n",
    "    qc.h(1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # For each bit (0 or 1) build a simple circuit block\n",
    "    for idx, bit in enumerate(bitstring[::-1]):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Initial H gate on control\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # If bit=1, do a CNOT gate\n",
    "        if int(bit):\n",
    "            qc.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "        # Final H gate to convert phase to computational-basis\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # Measure\n",
    "        qc.measure(0,idx)\n",
    "        # If not at the final bit, recycle and reset qubits\n",
    "        if idx != (len(bitstring)-1):\n",
    "            qc.barrier([0,1])\n",
    "            # Reset control qubit for reuse\n",
    "            qc.reset(0)\n",
    "            # reset target qubit to minimize dephasing\n",
    "            qc.reset(1)\n",
    "            #qc.barrier([0,1])\n",
    "            # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit again\n",
    "            qc.x(1)\n",
    "            qc.h(1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "567eea57",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us generate circuits for bit-string lengths of 2 -> 13:"
   ]
  },

   "execution_count": 138,
   "id": "9ac22d1d",
   "metadata": {

     "start_time": "2022-11-29T16:51:25.938930Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dyn_bv_circs = [dynamic_bv('1'*N) for N in range(2,13)]"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "58ffee0e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Measure+reset pair simplification\n",
    "\n",
    "Our current performance bottleneck is measure+reset pairs in the circuits, ie."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 84,
   "id": "4032fcf1",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-29T19:05:20.015685Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-29T19:05:19.909361Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 269.064x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 84,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 182,
       "width": 237
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(1, 1)\n",
    "qc.measure(0, 0)\n",
    "qc.reset(0)\n",
    "qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d6bdd96e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We have seen that a reset on IBM Quantum systems is itself a measurement followed by a conditional x-gate.  Thus the full circuit looks a bit like:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 85,
   "id": "c576e00c",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-29T19:05:24.789991Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-29T19:05:24.676098Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 352.675x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 85,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 182,
       "width": 305
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc2 = QuantumCircuit(1, 2)\n",
    "qc2.measure(0, 0)\n",
    "qc2.measure(0, 1)\n",
    "qc2.x(0).c_if(1, True)\n",
    "qc2.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "deab8bfa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we have already seen that measurements are the most error prone operations on IBM Quantum systems, and take quite a bit of time (~2 CX gates worth of time).  On this device, the average measurement error rate is"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 86,
   "id": "e57991cd",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-29T17:40:13.705592Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-29T17:40:13.692672Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.03262962962962961"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 86,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "np.mean([backend.properties().readout_error(kk) for kk in range(backend.num_qubits)])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a8e35b79",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So every `measure`+`reset` pair is quite costly in terms of both error and duration.  If we could reduce the number of measurements, then the performance would greatly improve.  It turns out that we can.  Specifically, when measuring the state of a quantum system $|\\psi\\rangle$, the state is projected onto one of the eigenstates of the corresponding measurement operator.  In this case that is one basis states in the computational basis.  Immediately after the measurement, the state would begin to evolve again until acted upon by another measurement or projective operation such as a noisy Kraus operator.  However, if our measurements act instantaneously, performing an additional measurement right after the first results in the exact same computational basis state, as the system has had no time to evolve.  This is an example of the Zeno effect; the state of a system is frozen upon fast repeated measurements.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can use this fact to drop the measurement originally included in the `reset`, and condition the x-gate on the result of the first measurement.  Because `measure`+`reset` are so ubiquitous in dynamic circuits, Qiskit can auto-simplify combinations of operations.  This is done via the `ResetAfterMeasureSimplification` transpiler pass:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 87,
   "id": "40936f0f",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-29T18:09:37.706793Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-29T18:09:37.701297Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "pm = PassManager(ResetAfterMeasureSimplification())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 88,
   "id": "745110ee",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-11-29T19:06:24.556946Z",
     "start_time": "2022-11-29T19:06:24.463151Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 269.064x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 88,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 182,
       "width": 237
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "collapsed_qc = pm.run(qc)\n",
    "collapsed_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "49251c6a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Optimized dynamic BV\n",
    "\n",
    "We are now in a position to further optimize our dynamic BV circuits by collapsing `measure`+`reset` pairs down to just a single measurement and conditional x-gate.  However, our barrier placement up until now prevents us from optimizing this via Qiskit.  As such, we need to define a new set of circuits:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 128,
   "id": "f44de731",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def dynamic_bv2(bitstring):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Create a Bernstein-Vazirani circuit from a given bitstring.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "        bitstring (str): A bitstring.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        QuantumCircuit: Output circuit.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(2, len(bitstring))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit\n",
    "    qc.x(1)\n",
    "    qc.h(1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # For each bit (0 or 1) build a simple circuit block\n",
    "    for idx, bit in enumerate(bitstring[::-1]):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Initial H gate on control\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # If bit=1, do a CNOT gate\n",
    "        if int(bit):\n",
    "            qc.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "        # Final H gate to convert phase to computational-basis\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # Measure\n",
    "        qc.barrier([0,1])\n",
    "        qc.measure(0,idx)\n",
    "        # If not at the final bit, recycle and reset qubits\n",
    "        if idx != (len(bitstring)-1):\n",
    "            # Reset control qubit for reuse\n",
    "            qc.reset(0)\n",
    "            # reset target qubit to minimize dephasing\n",
    "            qc.reset(1)\n",
    "            #qc.barrier([0,1])\n",
    "            # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit again\n",
    "            qc.x(1)\n",
    "            qc.h(1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "Nice!  We see that by being just a bit smarter, we have been able to greatly improve the fidelity of our dynamic BV circuits.  Because this simplification is so powerful, it is recommended to always use it when doing measurement+reset on IBM Quantum systems."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9020044e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## OpenQASM 3\n",
    "\n",
    "Up until now we have been using Qiskit to build quantum circuits.  This is of course the obvious thing to do, but directly building up circuits in Qiskit does have its limitations:\n",
    "\n",
    "    1. It is difficult to programmatically build a circuit, especially dynamic ones\n",
    "    2. They cannot be saved in a human readable format\n",
    "    3. They must be made in Python\n",
    "    4. They are not a serialization format\n",
    "    5. They are limited to Qiskit itself\n",
    "    \n",
    "For these reasons, and others, it is beneficial to have another way to create, store, and transmit quantum circuits.\n",
    "\n",
    "A completely platform-agnostic, text-based quantum circuit representation is provided by the [OpenQASM specification](https://openqasm.com/).  QASM, or quantum assembly language, has been around for almost 20 years, and OpenQASM is the primary flavor of the language.  The latest major release, version 3, brings better support for dynamic circuits and include the ability to interact with arbitrary classical code, pulse-level gate definitions, and support for explicit timing control.  QASM3 (also true for QASM2) is a Turing complete language, meaning in principle it can perform any computation, if given enough resources (memory and time).\n",
    "\n",
    "QASM3 is a very convenient format for working with quantum circuits with conditional operations and creating circuits in a universal format from any language where a QASM parser exists.  That is to say that QASM3 will allow one to create circuits from any language (C/C++, Rust, Fortran, Matlab, etc...) and allow them to be executed on IBM Quantum hardware.  \n",
    "\n",
    "For now, lets take a look at a QASM3 representation of one of our optimized BV circuits:"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 156,
   "id": "ad18ed22",

    }

      "include \"stdgates.inc\";\n",

      "sx q[0];\n",
      "rz(pi/2) q[0];\n",
      "rz(pi/2) q[1];\n",
      "sx q[1];\n",
      "rz(-pi/2) q[1];\n",
      "cx q[0], q[1];\n",
      "rz(pi/2) q[0];\n",
      "sx q[0];\n",
      "rz(pi/2) q[0];\n",
      "barrier q[0], q[1];\n",
      "reset q[1];\n",
      "rz(pi/2) q[1];\n",
      "sx q[1];\n",
      "rz(-pi/2) q[1];\n",
      "c[0] = measure q[0];\n",
      "if (c[0] == 1) {\n",

      "sx q[0];\n",
      "rz(pi/2) q[0];\n",
      "barrier q[0], q[1];\n",
      "reset q[1];\n",

      "c[1] = measure q[0];\n",

      "rz(pi/2) q[0];\n",
      "sx q[0];\n",
      "rz(pi/2) q[0];\n",
      "barrier q[0], q[1];\n",
      "c[2] = measure q[0];\n",
      "\n"
     ]
